==Catholic doctrine==
The article should perhaps allow some space to expose what Catholic doctrine on the topic actually is, instead of deriving various misconceptions from it. The Church's doctrine is not that every sperm is sacred, but rather that every embryo is sacred (see [[creationism (soul)]]). The moral teaching is that every human person is willed by God at the moment of their biological conception. This view is neatly exposed in the recent magisterial document [[Dignitas Personae]], on the dignity of the human person. However, it should be made clear that the Church's opposition to contraception and its opposition to embryonic termination are not the same thing, since both are separate parts of [[Catholic moral theology]] that are covered in different sections of [[Humanae Vitae]]. [[User:ADM|ADM]] ([[User talk:ADM|talk]]) 19:09, 1 May 2009 (UTC)

The song speaks to the questions the children put to their father. Why not use contraception? Why not sterilization? Nothing in the skit mentions embryos. It's obvious that you put work into your response, but you're answering a question that has no relevance here.  <span style="font-size: smaller;" class="autosigned">—Preceding [[Wikipedia:Signatures|unsigned]] comment added by [[Special:Contributions/64.66.99.129|64.66.99.129]] ([[User talk:64.66.99.129|talk]]) 19:08, 14 December 2009 (UTC)</span><!-- Template:UnsignedIP --> <!--Autosigned by SineBot-->

